  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering, including:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Documenting potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Compliance regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Implementing Anti-Money Laundering (AML) programs\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n\n4. Transaction monitoring\n- Tracking unusual financial activities\n- Identifying potential money laundering patterns\n- Investigating high-risk transactions\n\n5. Employee training\n- Educating staff about money laundering risks\n- Teaching detection and reporting procedures\n- Maintaining ongoing compliance awareness\n\n6. Record-keeping\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n- Preserving customer identification documents\n- Ensuring documentation for potential investigations\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, fines, and potential criminal charges for financial institutions.",
